BARD SONGS AND PERFORMANCE

Battle songs are different from simple lute practice. They create a bardic
song field in the room for a short time, pulse effects while they last, and
feed the Bard's Performance.

Performance is a 0-100 momentum meter shown with bscore. It
rises when you keep songs moving and falls when combat momentum stalls or your
voice is disrupted. Repeating the same kind of song builds less Performance
than keeping the music varied. Charisma improves Performance gains, song field
strength, song field duration, and the rewards from hidden harmonies.

Battle songs use musical cooldown families. Each song form has its own short
recovery, so a Rhythm song does not lock out Melody, Harmony, or Dissonance.
This is intentional: Bards are meant to build momentum by changing forms. A
tiny song cadence cooldown still prevents button-mashing, and repeating the
same form waits on that form's timer.

When Performance crests into a Crescendo, you have a brief Finale window. Use
bmon or bscore to watch for it, then spend it with echoburst,
battlefieldsilence, or Wail.

Song forms:
   Rhythm       timing, movement, attack cadence
   Melody       morale, recovery, emotional control
   Harmony      group amplification
   Dissonance   disruption and weakening
   Crescendo    burst pressure
   Finale       high-impact endings

